nalysis to subagents\n    27→- For complex problems, throw more compute at it via subagents\n    28→- One task per subagent for focused execution\n    29→- Subagents should generally be isolated in worktrees\n    30→\n    31→### 3. Self-Improvement Loop\n    32→- After corrections that reveal a recurring pattern: update memory with the lesson\n    33→- Write rules for yourself that prevent the same class of mistake\n    34→- Review relevant lessons at session start\n    35→\n    36→### 4. Verification Before Done\n    37→- Never mark a task complete without proving it works\n    38→- Diff behavior between main and your changes when relevant\n    39→\n    40→### 5. Demand Elegance (Balanced)\n    41→- If a fix feels hacky, flag it and propose the elegant alternative\n    42→- Skip this for simple, obvious fixes — don't over-engineer\n    43→\n    44→### 6. Autonomous Bug Fixing\n    45→- When given a bug report with clear reproduction: first write an automated test that reproduces the bug, then fix it\n    46→- Point at logs, errors, failing tests — then resolve them\n    47→- Zero context switching required from the user\n    48→- Ambiguous scope or multi-system impact: plan first, then fix\n    49→\n    50→## Core Principles\n    51→- **No Laziness**: Find root causes. No temporary fixes. Senior developer standards.\n    52→"}]},"uuid":"76884f7c-89d9-4b8c-931f-168e31f64d9f","timestamp":"2026-03-08T19:13:16.588Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"36356cb3-2196-47f4-9806-32b66a02ad95"}
